Each year there will be a surplus and this is added onto the initial capital. The capital can either be re-invested as an another input (better farm machinery for example) or it can be legally extracted by the owners, either privately or publicly. The latter form capital markets, where the shares in the harvest are also traded.&nbsp;</p>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="120" width="690" x="40" y="525" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell Extraction</h1><p>Fig. 1 shows capital progress without extraction by an external party. Comparing the two figures, the last two capital values of the balance sheet (green in Fig.1)&nbsp; are now yellow. The difference between the opening capital and closing (red and green dots) is therefore reduced leading to diminished funds for the business. div.p: In order for the extraction in Fig 2. to take place, there must be a functional mechanism to shift the polarity of profit from positive to negative. Owners have evolved a recording surface to facilitate the process, with the intent to extract a periodic harvest. That is why conventional accounting systems are inherently unresponsive to transaction grained reporting. Its roots are in orchestrating the polarity shift from a Company perspective, and not orchestrating the financial dimensions of Production.
